ement and in the availability of social support. They illustrate diversity among older adults in social inclusion and in the types of services that are essential to their well being. For the first time, detailed information is provided on characteristics of rural communities that make them supportive to different groups of older adults. Comparisons between the UK and North America highlight similarities in how landscapes create rural identities, and fundamental differences in how climate, distance and rural culture shape the everyday lives of older adults.  Rural ageing is a valuable resource for students, academics and practitioners interested in communities, rural settings and ageing and the lifecourse. Rich in national profiles and grounded in the narratives of older adults, it provides theoretical, empirical and practical examples of growing old in rural communities never before presented.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRural elderlyxServices for. 0aRural elderlyxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBartlam, Bernadette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Sherry Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChappell, Neena L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobbs, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDosman, Donna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEales, Jacquie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFast, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibbens, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGierveld, Jenny de Jong, econtr